Current test case analysis:
Input: {"a": "}"} tail

The escape sequence branch (lines 699-702) is hit when:
1. We're in_str (inside a quoted string)
2. Previous character was a backslash (escaped = True)
3. OR current character is a backslash (to set escaped = True)

Testing with actual escape sequences:
escaped quote: {"a": "\""} -> {"a": "\""}
escaped newline: {"a": "\n"} -> {"a": "\n"}
escaped backslash: {"a": "\\"} -> {"a": "\\"}

Testing mitigation: json.loads validation
============================================================

Valid JSON with escaped quotes: {"value": "text\"with\"escaped", "other": 123}
_first_balanced_json result: {"value": "text\"with\"escaped", "other": 123}
json.loads succeeds: {'value': 'text"with"escaped', 'other': 123}

Verifying _extract_json also validates:
_extract_json succeeds: {'value': 'text"with"escaped', 'other': 123}

MITIGATION ANALYSIS:
Even if _first_balanced_json has an escape bug, the
subsequent json.loads() at line 670 would catch it.
The JSONDecodeError is caught and re-raised as ReasoningError.

Testing if escape sequence handling is ACTUALLY broken:
============================================================

Testing _first_balanced_json with escape sequences:

Input:  {"key": "\""}
Desc:   JSON with escaped quote at end of string
Result: {"key": "\""}
Parsed: {'key': '"'}

Input:  {"key": "\"middle\""}
Desc:   JSON with escaped quotes in middle
Result: {"key": "\"middle\""}
Parsed: {'key': '"middle"'}

Input:  {"key": "before\"after"}
Desc:   JSON with escaped quote between text
Result: {"key": "before\"after"}
Parsed: {'key': 'before"after'}

Input:  {"key": "\\"} tail
Desc:   JSON with escaped backslash, then closing
Result: {"key": "\\"}
